subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.

Alsodes cantillanensis

can be distinguished from all other congeneric species for the following combination of characters: 
1
) thorny patches of the chest of males with spines uniformly distributed; 
2
) head with a triangle between the posterior border of the eyes and the snout tip, which contrasts with the background coloration; 
3
) superior part of the iris gold-yellowish brilliant, almost uniform; 
4
) postocular fold well-developed, extending beyond of the insertions of arms; 
5
) snout slightly truncated in dorsal and lateral profile; 
6
) dorsal skin smooth; 
7
) dorsal coloration ochre (
holotype
) or orange (
paratype
), with small and diffuse dark spots irregularly distributed; and 
8
) posterior legs slightly barred.
